This species, known as the ribbed pine borer, is restricted to Pinaceae , having larval hosts in at least six genera in North America (Linsley and Chemsak 1997; Vlasak and Vlasakova 2002;
Majka et al. 2007
; Guarnieri 2010 ). It generally metamorphoses into an adult in fall and spends the winter to early spring in a unique pupal cell that was illustrated by Hess (1920) , Craighead (1950) , and others.
